An [octagram](/Octagram) is, to put it mildly, an eight-angled [star polygon](/Star_polygon). A shape that, much like certain individuals, insists on being noticed through its self-intersecting nature. If you’re here, presumably you’ve managed to grasp that much.

### Regular Octagram

It’s a [regular star polygon](/Regular_star_polygon), naturally. Possessing precisely eight [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) and eight [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) – a rather predictable count, one might observe. Its identity, for those who appreciate such labels, is formally etched into existence by the [Schläfli symbol](/Schl%C3%A4fli_symbol) {8/3}. This isn’t some arcane incantation, just a concise way of stating it’s an 8-pointed star formed by connecting every third vertex of a regular octagon. One could almost call it elegant, if one were inclined towards sentimentality.

For the visually inclined, or those who require exhaustive notation, it can also be denoted as t{4/3} within the realm of [Coxeter–Dynkin diagrams](/Coxeter%E2%80%93Dynkin_diagram). Its inherent balance is reflected in its [symmetry group](/List_of_planar_symmetry_groups), which is undeniably [Dihedral](/Dihedral_symmetry) (D 8 ), indicating eight rotational and eight reflectional symmetries. Each internal angle, for those keeping score, measures a precise 45 [degrees](/Degree_(angle)).

As for its properties, it ticks all the usual boxes for a well-behaved star: it is a [star](/Star_polygon) polygon, inherently [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon) (meaning all its vertices lie on a single circumcircle), [equilateral](/Equilateral_polygon) (all sides are of equal length), [isogonal](/Isogonal_figure) (all vertices are equivalent), and [isotoxal](/Isotoxal_figure) (all edges are equivalent). Its [dual polygon](/Dual_polygon)? It’s itself, a rather fitting touch for something so self-contained.

### Star Polygons

Humanity seems to have a peculiar fascination with repeating patterns, particularly those that fold back on themselves. The octagram is merely one entry in a surprisingly extensive catalogue of such geometric diversions. Others include:

*   The rather ubiquitous [pentagram](/Pentagram)
*   The somewhat less common [hexagram](/Hexagram)
