#### Usage

The octagram, in its various guises, has been adopted across cultures and belief systems, a testament to its compelling visual appeal. It seems humans are consistently drawn to patterns that hint at both order and complexity.

*   The [Rub el Hizb](/Rub_el_Hizb) – a prominent Islamic character often used in the Quran.
*   The [Seljuk star](/Seljuk_star) – a significant symbol in [Seljuk](/Seljuk) art and architecture.
*   The [Shamsa](/Shamsa) – an intricate medallion or sunburst motif found in Islamic art, often employing octagrammatic patterns.
*   The [Star of Ishtar](/Star_of_Ishtar) – an ancient symbol representing the Sumerian goddess [Inanna](/Inanna) and her East Semitic counterpart [Ishtar](/Ishtar), and later associated with the Roman goddess [Venus](/Venus).
*   The symbol of [Seshat](/Seshat) – the [hieroglyph](/Hieroglyph) representing this ancient Egyptian goddess of wisdom and writing often depicts a seven-petaled flower, which, with its stem, forms a stylized octagram.
*   The [Star of Lakshmi](/Star_of_Lakshmi) – an Indian character composed of two overlapping squares, representing the eight forms of wealth (Ashta Lakshmi) associated with the goddess [Lakshmi](/Lakshmi).
*   The [Surya Majapahit](/Surya_Majapahit) – a solar emblem used during the [Majapahit](/Majapahit) Empire in Indonesia, intended to represent the [Hindu](/Hindu) gods associated with the cardinal directions.
*   The [Compass rose](/Compass_rose) – a navigational tool that uses an octagonal star to represent the [cardinal directions](/Cardinal_directions) and the eight [principal winds](/Principal_winds).
*   The [Auseklis](/Auseklis) – a powerful symbol in Latvian mythology, often depicted as a regular octagram, associated with the morning star and protection.
*   The [Guñelve](/Gu%C3%B1elve) – a representation of [Venus](/Venus) in [Mapuche](/Mapuche) iconography, often depicted as an octagram.
*   The [Selburose](/Selburose) – a traditional Norwegian design motif, frequently featuring a regular octagram, often seen in knitting patterns.
*   The symbol of [Utu](/Utu) – an ancient [Mesopotamian](/Mesopotamian) god symbol, often depicted as a star, representing the Sun god and justice.
*   The [Thieves' Star](/Russian_criminal_tattoos) – a [Post-Soviet](/Post-Soviet_states) criminal tattoo symbol, known in [Russian](/Russian_language) as «восьмиконечник», often signifying a "thief in law" or a high-ranking criminal.

